package com.get_tt_right.gatewayserver;

import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.cloud.gateway.route.RouteLocator;
import org.springframework.cloud.gateway.route.builder.RouteLocatorBuilder;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;

import java.time.LocalDateTime;

/**Update as of 06/7/2026
 * ------------------------
 * Choreography Saga Pattern
 * --------------------------
 * Inside our ms's, since we are looking to implement the Choreography Saga Pattern, we need to make sure all our ms's are communicating asynchronously with the events. To implement event driven style of communication inside our ms's we need to adopt 2 different projects from the Spring ecosystem. The very 1st one is Spring cloud Stream which is going to help you to stream the events to the message queues like RabbitMQ or Kafka, etc. The 2nd project is Spring Cloud Functions - With the help of Spring Cloud functions we can convert our Java methods into REST API components. So, as a developer we don't have to create REST API's manually by using lot many annotations. Instead, what we can do is, we can create normal Java methods and let the Spring Cloud function expose them as the REST APIs. This approach is going to be super helpful because inside the event driven ms's, we need to build lot many APIs which can be invoked by other ms's.
 * 1st I will open the pom.xml file of one of the ms's i.e., lets try to start with customer ms. Just after the "...eureka-client" dependency I am going to add 2 dependencies i.e., spring-cloud-stream and spring-cloud-stream-binder-rabbit. Since I am looking to use RabbitMQ as an infrastructural component we need to make sure we are adding this "spring-cloud-stream-binder-rabbit" dependency. And, we don't have to specifically add the Spring Cloud Functions dependency because whenever we are using Spring Cloud Stream dependency, behind the scenes Spring cloud functions dependency will be downloaded automatically. Now, load the maven changes. Next, you can jump into the Spring cloud stream by ctrl + clicking on it in the pom.xml. Here, you should be able to see lot many other transitive dependency including those related to the Spring cloud function i.e., "spring-cloud-function-context". If you again jump inside it, again it will take you to another pom.xml with lot many other transitive dependencies as well where you will be able to see dependencies like, "spring-cloud-function-core", ...etc. This confirms that whenever we add Spring cloud Stream related dependency, we don't have to specifically add the Spring Cloud Function related dependencies because whenever we are using Spring Cloud Stream dependency, behind the scenes Spring cloud function related dependencies will be downloaded automatically. Hope the visualization we have had has convinced you.
 * Now, same drill, add the same 2 dependencies i.e., spring-cloud-stream and spring-cloud-stream-binder-rabbit to the pom.xml of the account ms, cards, loans ms. Since we only have these 4 ms's which are going to be involved inside the Choreography Saga Pattern, we thus need to make changes inside these 4 pom.xml files. As a next step, since we are building event driven ms's we need to set up either RabbitMQ or Kafka inside our local system. Since RabbitMQ is very easy to set up compared to Kafka, I choose RabbitMQ. Now, lets try to create a RabbitMQ container quickly so that our ms's can connect to this container and use this RabbitMQ container for event driven communication. To start the RabbitMQ container, we need to know the docker command that we can leverage. To know this command you can go to the https://www.rabbitmq.com/ website >> Click on docs tab >> Here on the LHS nav, there is a link with "Install and Upgrade' on which you need to click and here you should be able to see the docker command that we can use. Copy it and execute it in your warp terminal. This is going to start my RabbitMQ inside my system. Don't try to disturb this terminal because right now inside this terminal only the rabbitMQ is running. If you try to pres CTrl + C or if you try to close this terminal then your RabbitMQ container is going to be stopped. Once the RabbitMQ container is started we need to mention the RabbitMQ connection details inside the application.yml files of the respective 4 ms's.
 * Inside the application.yml of customer ms, under the spring parent property, we need to create/mention a new element with the name "rabbitmq". Do this just after the "jpa" related configuration. The "rabbitmq" related configuration are., host, port, username, pwd, connection-timeout. By default, the username and pwd are going to have the value of "guest" and the same we are trying to use here. Same drill, paste these rabbitmq related configurations in the other ms's i.e., accounts, loans and cards. After this, the next step is - create a Dto which can be used as a request input to the update mobile number API. Since this Dto is going to be used across all the ms's - I want to create this Dto under the common project i.e., MobileNumberUpdateDto. Once our Dto class is ready, as a next step, I will go to the customer ms and inside the CustomerController class I will try to create a new API - As of now, inside this class we only have the CRUD operation related API's . Inside this class we will create a new API of type @PatchMapping with the API path i.e., /mobile-number - the api name can be anything, but we just choose this. Check the docstring of that API for more details.
 * You can revisit all the code that we have written as part of this Choreography Saga pattern and make sure there are no copy and paste mistakes. Next, we can try testing the overall happy path flow of the Choreography Saga pattern. Hahah! as you know we have only done half the job as far as this pattern is concerned by implementing only the happy path - we are yet to develop the logic around the compensating transactions. But 1st, let's make sure this happy path is working followed by we can then proceed to focusing on the error/exception scenarios.
 *
 * Demo of the Choreography Saga Pattern happy flow
 * -------------------------------------------------
 * Start all you ms's as guided in the documentation "Testing our services locally in ide - steps". Once you start all the ms's, you can go to the browser and try to access the RabbitMQ url - http://localhost:15672 . If you recall, we started a RabbitMQ container to support the asynchronous communication inside our ms's. Here, we can validate few of the things. 1st under the connections tab if you see, there are 4 different connections which are nothing but our ms's themselves. We have customer, accounts, cards and loans which are trying to connect with the RabbitMQ. That's why we are able to see 4 different connections. If you click on the exchanges tab, you should be able to see 4 different exchanges with the custom destination names that we have defined in our streaming and function definitions inside the respective application.yml files of our ms's. Customer ms will send the message to the destination which is update-account-mobile-number followed by accounts ms will send the message to the destination which is update-card-mobile-number. Cards ms will send the message/event to update-account-mobile-number destination. At last the loans ms will publish an  overall status event/message to the customer ms using the destination - update-mobile-number-status. So, all the exchanges/topics/destinations are ready. If you go to the queues and streams tab, you should be able to see 4 different queues with the custom names that we have defined in our streaming and function definitions inside the respective application.yml files of our ms's. So, those are all the queues and to those queues only, our ms's they are enrolled. So, basically what is going to happen is whenever someone publishes a message/an event to a given exchange(s)/destination(s)/topic(s) - for the ms's which are listening to this exchange(s) the messages/events will be forwarded to the queues of those ms's. The queues are automatically created by the Spring Cloud Stream and Spring Cloud Functions. If you are observant, you can be able to see that the queue name will be the "destination/topic/exchange name"."application/ms name" i.e., update-account-mobile-number.accounts. If we have 10 different instances of accounts ms running, they are going to enroll to the same queue because inside the application.yml we have mentioned the "group" configurations as the application name itself.
 * All the instances which enrolled to the same queue we can call them as a consumer group. One of the instance inside this consumer group they are going to read the message from this queue and the remaining consumers, they will simply seat back and relax haha or they will pick some other messages available inside the queue. This gives a confirmation to us that RabbitMQ set up is working properly. As a next step, in the postman, 1st we are going to create some data. I will create a customer with the mobile number "3254537678" - create successfully. Next I will create account, card and loan using the same mobile number - Like this we have successfully created all the data inside all the ms's with a given mobile number. We can validate if the data is successfully or not by invoking the fetchCustomerSummery API available inside the gateway server. Like this you should get all the customer, account, card and loan information. Next, I want to update the mobile number in all the ms's using the new API that we have built. If you go to the customer folder, there is a request with the name choreography-mobile-number. Before we try to invoke the send button you can go to your respective ms's (customer, accounts, cards and finally loans) consoles and clear all the log messages. Now if you click on the send button you should see we are getting a successful response! Now, lets validate if the Choreography Saga flow is executed properly based on how we configured our streaming and function related configurations and logic by going to the ms's logs. We know that the request will 1st be recieved by the customers application and here if you scroll down you should be able to see a log statement that says "Is the updateAccountMobileNumber request successfully triggered ? : true" Yes, it is triggered successfully. Next we also have a log statement that says, "Received  updateMobileNumberStatus request  for the details: MobileNumberUpdateDto(currentMobileNumber=3254537678, newMobileNumber=3254537671)" This confirms that the loans ms triggered the event conveying the overall saga pattern txn/business flow is completed. Now, inside the accounts console >> As we know that from the customer ms the request will go to the Accounts ms and here you should be able to see a logger "Is the updateCardMobileNumber request successfully triggered ? : true" This logger confirms that the accounts ms triggered a message to the card ms. If you go to the cards application console, here also we have a logger which is "Is the updateLoanMobileNumber request successfully triggered ? : true". This logger confirms that the cards ms triggered a message to the loans ms. Now, lets go to the loans ms console, and here also we have a logger which is "Is the updateMobileNumberStatus request successfully triggered ? : true". This logger confirms that the loans ms triggered a message to the customer ms. Now, all the ms's are in sync and the choreography saga pattern is executed successfully. From this loggers, you should now be having crisp clarity that the distributed txn travelled throught my respective ms's as designed and as expected.
 * Very similarly, based upon your business requirements, you can make your distributed txn flow travel across services and in the same order the txn is going to be executed. Just to confirm that everything is updated inside the backend respective DB's as well, what we will do is - we will take this new mobile number and try to invoke the API that we have inside the gateway server to fetch the customer summary. If you try to invoke the fetchCustomerSummery API with the new mobile number, you should be able to see the updated details. But 1st you could try with the old mobile number 1st and you can see we are getting some exception which maybe we have not handled properly but this gives us a confirmation that their is no data available for the old mobile number. Now if you give the new mobile number then you should be able to see the updated mobile number in all the ms's. Hurreeey! With this you should be happy with the progress that we are making as right now, our Choreography Saga pattern is executed successfully foer the happy flow. As a next step we should think about how to handle the exceptions and how to trigger the compensating trsansactions.
 *
 * Implementing Compensation Transactions
 * ---------------------------------------
 * While designing the compensation txns, you need to think of all the possibilities and all the places where your code can go wrong, or it can throw an Exception. That's why let's try to follow the same strategy. Imagine one of the end-users is trying to send a request to the /mobile-number API. The request will be processed by the customer ms. First, let's imagine that an RTE can happen inside this customer ms itself before the customer ms tries to dispatch an event/message to the accounts ms. As an initial step, let's try to handle the same. In the CustomerServiceImpl class where we are trying to make the DB updates in regard to updating the mobile number. Check its docstring for more details.
 * With this we have done all the changes - next, we will try to validate/demo the compensation flow alongside the happy flow.
 *
 * Demo of Complete Choreography Saga Pattern
 * -------------------------------------------
 * Review all the changes we have done so far and now let's go ahead and test the negative scenario flow. To test all the changes we have done so far, 1st we will try to throw an intentional RTE inside my loans ms bcs in the Saga pattern flow, the loans ms is the last service which is going to update the mobile number. If there is an exception occurs in the loans ms, then the compensation txns inside the cards, accounts and customers ms's they have to be executed. That's why, let's try to throw some RTE from the loans ms inside the method updateMobileNumber just after the line of code loansRepository.save(loans); (Just after saving the data into the loans DB). And make sure to comment all the subsequent lines of code in that method to avoid CE's. Now, you can spin up your services and supporting components by following the steps documented in "Testing our services locally in ide - steps". Now, inside postman, we will try to create some brand-new data with the mobile number 3254537688. 1st create Customer, then account, Card and finally loan data. Once done, invoke the fetchCustomerSummary API with the mobile number 3254537688. You should be able to see customer, account, loan and card data for the mobile number 3254537688. Now lets go to the choreography-mobile-number API and invoke it by passing the currentMobileNumber as 3254537688 and the newMobileNumber as 3254537671. As soon as I click on the send button, behind the scenes the updation of the mobile number will get triggered and the client will get the 200 status message in the response to confirm that the trigger has been fired. Why nit wait until the response is back? haha! Simple - Becuase we are following the asynchronous communication. So, by the immediate response we are getting of 200, client should not assume that that is the overal status. Usually in this kind of scenarios, we need to let the client applications to continously poll the backend service to know whether a distributed txn is completed successfully or not. And btw, for visualization on your local test, before you click on the send button of the request choreography-mobile-number, clean the console of your services i.e., customer, accounts, cards and finally loans service as we want to ascertain our tests.
 * If you click on the send button, you can see we are getting a success message haha! but behind the scenes we know very well that the rollback may have happened and the mobile number is not going to be updated in any of our 4 services. It is going to stay as the same old mobile number. If you check the loans application console you can see that we have some error logs there which we logged from the catch block followed by you will be able to see some loggers indicating that the compensation txn on the card ms is triggered i.e., "Sending rollbackCardMobileNumber request for the details: MobileNumberUpdateDto(currentMobileNumber=3254537688, newMobileNumber=3254537671)". In the cards ms console, you should also be able to see a log message confirming that the compensation txn on the account ms is triggered i.e., "Sending rollbackAccountMobileNumber request for the details: MobileNumberUpdateDto(currentMobileNumber=3254537688, newMobileNumber=3254537671)". If you go to the accounts ms here also we have a log message confirming that the customer ms compensation txn is triggered i.e., "Sending rollbackCustomerMobileNumber request for the details: MobileNumberUpdateDto(currentMobileNumber=3254537688, newMobileNumber=3254537671)". At last inside customers application console you should be able to see a log message saying that "Received  rollbackCustomerMobileNumber request  for the details: MobileNumberUpdateDto(currentMobileNumber=3254537688, newMobileNumber=3254537671)". This gives us a confirmation that the Saga pattern is working perfectly based upon the logic that we have written. We can also try to validate this by invoking the gatewayserver API i.e., fetchCustomerSummary. What we will do is, we will try passing the new mobile number to the request and as can be seen in the response we are getting a RTE because there is no data whereas if we pass the current/old mobile number then we will get a successful response and the beauty is all the customer, account, card and loan related data all have the same mobile number which is 3254537688. Now, let's try to test the happy path/flow scenario one more time. What you can do is, comment the RTE we introduced explicitly in the loans ms LoansServiceImpl in the method#updateMobileNumber just after the line of code loansRepository.save(loans); and then uncomment the subsequent line of code in this method.
 * This time you can try to invoke the same API i.e., choreography-mobile-number with the same new mobile number 3254537671. As soon as you click on the send button you should get a successful response as expected becuase as we noted this is asynchronous communication and we should not keep the client waiting. Now if you poll the request fetchCustomerSummary API for the actual status, you should be able to see the mobile number is updated to the new mobile number 3254537671 in all the ms's but if you try passing the old mobile number while invoking the fetchCustomerSummary API, you should get a response with some RTE.Heeyyy!! this confirms that both the happy path and the exception path of our Choreography Saga pattern is working just fine as expected. With the progress we have made so far you should be super happy! And right now you have crisp clarity how "Complex" it is to implement these changes around Choreography Saga pattern. When we say complex, haha!, we don't mean that it is complex to implement this business logic, it just means you need to CAREFULLY! design you Saga txn flow thinking of all the possible error/exception scenarios and according you need to build the compensation txns as well. That's how subtle it can be!. Think and think clearly always. Consider yourself having the stepping stone knowledge around Choreography Saga pattern. As a next step we will start exploring the Orchestartion Saga pattern which we can use along with the CQRS pattern. Check tis out inthe 00_start project for more details.
 *
 * */
@SpringBootApplication
public class GatewayserverApplication {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(GatewayserverApplication.class, args);
    }

    @Bean
    public RouteLocator eazyBankRouteConfig(RouteLocatorBuilder routeLocatorBuilder) {
        return routeLocatorBuilder.routes()
                .route(p -> p
                        .path("/eazybank/customer/**")
                        .filters(f -> f.rewritePath("/eazybank/customer/(?<segment>.*)", "/${segment}")
                                .addResponseHeader("X-Response-Time", LocalDateTime.now().toString()))
                        .uri("lb://CUSTOMER"))
                .route(p -> p
                        .path("/eazybank/accounts/**")
                        .filters(f -> f.rewritePath("/eazybank/accounts/(?<segment>.*)", "/${segment}")
                                .addResponseHeader("X-Response-Time", LocalDateTime.now().toString()))
                        .uri("lb://ACCOUNTS"))
                .route(p -> p
                        .path("/eazybank/loans/**")
                        .filters(f -> f.rewritePath("/eazybank/loans/(?<segment>.*)", "/${segment}")
                                .addResponseHeader("X-Response-Time", LocalDateTime.now().toString()))
                        .uri("lb://LOANS"))
                .route(p -> p
                        .path("/eazybank/cards/**")
                        .filters(f -> f.rewritePath("/eazybank/cards/(?<segment>.*)", "/${segment}")
                                .addResponseHeader("X-Response-Time", LocalDateTime.now().toString()))
                        .uri("lb://CARDS")).build();


    }


}
